Week 8 — School Ranking Data

Homework for Week 8 of DATS 2102

Mapping: Fundamentals of geographic data visualization.

Learning Goals:

  • Distinguish vector vs. raster and common formats (Shapefile, GeoJSON, TopoJSON)
  • Explain/document CRS & projections; reproject appropriately
  • Design choropleths (normalization, classification, color, legends)
  • Perform spatial/attribute joins; enrich with ACS; build interactive maps

Agenda:

  1. Pick a geographic unit (country/state/county/tract) + a topic.

Build a reproducible pipeline (notebook) that includes:

  1. One static choropleth with clear legend + caption.
  2. One interactive map (Folium or Plotly) with at least two layers (e.g., choropleth + points) and tooltips.
  3. At least one join (spatial or attribute) and appropriate normalization.

Finally:

  1. A 150–250 word reflection on design choices, denominators, classification, CRS, and limitations.
  2. Submit .ipynb and .html.

(1) Select your dataset

Task: Let’s take a look at our dataset.

(1a) What is our dataset?

Looking at all states in 2018, this dataset is concerned with school rankings according to multiple different ranking systems. This dataset comes from Social Explorer website where it had been compiled from SchoolDigger.com.

Here, I will be analyzing the school ranking data, especially middle school data, through mapping. Some research questions I will tackle are:

  • How do the middle school ranks change across the country?
  • Do we see any regions with certain common ranks or related ranks?
  • Are there any surprises in the middle school ranks of certain states?

(1d) Inspect

The variables in this dataset have specified names, so let’s understand those before we start.

Geographical variables:

  • Geo_QNAME: Qualifying Name
  • Geo_NAME: Name of Area
  • Geo_FIPS: FIPS
  • Geo_NATION: Nation
  • Geo_STATE: State

School ranking variables:

  • SE_T001_003: SchoolDigger Number of Stars Middle
  • SE_T001_006: SchoolDigger Rank Middle
  • SE_T001_009: SchoolDigger Rank Of Middle

Now, let’s make a static choropleth map that shows SchoolDigger Number of Stars Middle per US state:

Code 
import geopandas as gpd, pandas as pd
ax = g.plot(column="SE_T001_003",
    cmap="Blues",
    scheme="Quantiles",
    k=5,
    legend=True,
    legend_kwds= dict(title="Number of Stars Middle",loc='upper left', bbox_to_anchor=(1.01, 1)),
    edgecolor="black",
    linewidth=0.2)
ax.set_axis_off()

(3) Interactive Choropleth

Task: One interactive map (Folium or Plotly) with at least two layers (e.g., choropleth + points) and tooltips.

Since we’ve already merged the geographic data with the school rank data, we can simply create this map now. First, I will make an interactive map with folium that shows SchoolDigger Number of Stars Middle:

Code 
import folium
m = folium.Map(location=[38.9, -77.0], zoom_start=4, tiles="cartodbpositron")
folium.Choropleth(
    geo_data=polys,
    name="SE_T001_003",
    data=g,
    columns=["NAME","SE_T001_003"],
    key_on="feature.properties.NAME",
    fill_opacity=0.75, line_opacity=0.2, legend_name="Number of Stars Middle"
).add_to(m)
folium.LayerControl().add_to(m)
m

Code 
import pandas as pd

merged["SE_T001_006"] = pd.to_numeric(merged["SE_T001_006"], errors="coerce")
merged["V1T005001"]   = pd.to_numeric(merged["V1T005001"], errors="coerce")

PER = 1000
den = merged["V1T005001"].clip(lower=1)
merged["SE_T001_006_percap"] = merged["SE_T001_006"].div(den).mul(PER)
Code 
import geopandas as gpd, pandas as pd
ax = merged.plot(column="SE_T001_006_percap",
    cmap="Blues",
    scheme="Quantiles",
    k=5,
    legend=True,
    legend_kwds= dict(title="Rank Normalized",loc='upper left', bbox_to_anchor=(1.01, 1)),
    edgecolor="black",
    linewidth=0.2)
ax.set_axis_off()

(5) Reflection

Task: A 150–250 word reflection on design choices, denominators, classification, CRS, and limitations.

Overall, throughout our visualizations we saw that more populated states were consistently ranked higher. This is why normalizing by population is so important since these states could be being ranked so high based on an unfair advantage in population. However, we cannot take even this data without futher questioning and looking deeper since our normalized map shows that now less populated states have the advantage. It is possible that merely states with higher populations receive more funding and therefore have better ranked schools.

It is also interesting to note from these maps that not only states with high populations (California, Florida, Texas, etc) but also states in the Mid-West and parts of New England are highly ranked.

Throughout this process I made a few design choices. One of the first choices I made was in picking a color scheme where darker/heavier colors would indicate high ranking instead of low ranking. This I decided both since these states would be more visible and since the majority of the country was not so highly ranked and having the whole country be in dark colors would be difficult to look at.

There were a few small choices I made as well. I decided on a blue color scheme as that felt relatively neutral to reflect the topic at hand and if anything, blue is often related to intellectual and academic pursuits. I also bordered my static maps in black to make the state borders more legible.
